Gene ontology file organization:
- what is always present:
  - [Term] :this signals the start of a new term
  - id
  - name
  - namespace: biological_process or molecular_function or cellular_component
  - def: "definition" [links to scientific papers,]
- optional tags:
  - comment
  - synonym: "name of term" + EXACT/RELATED/NARROW + [ ]
  - is_a: term_id ! description
  - is_obsolete: true, otherwise by default false
  - alt_id
  - replaced_by
  - consider
  - xref
  - relationship: part of, regulates, ...
  - subset


GO Associatiole File (GAF) organization (tab-separated attributes):
1. Database, ex. UniProtKB
2. Unique ID of the term from the database referenced in (1)
3. A name for the term, in the form of object symbol
4. Relation, ex. contributes_to, NOT|enables, enables...
5. GO id for the term related to our object
6. 1+ identifiers for a single reference cited as the source experiment or method for atributing the GO ID to the DB Object ID. 
  If there are multiple links, they are separated by | and no spaces
7. Evidence code
8. With/from (reference to another object)
9. Identifies the namespace of the GO term: P (biological process), F (molecular function) or C (cellular component) (this is redundant info in theory)
10. DB object name (human readable)
11. DB object synonym
12. DB object type
13. Taxon (NBCI taxonomy identifier)
14. Date (YYYYMMDD)
15. Assigned by: the database that made the annotation
16. Annotation extension (optional)
17. Gene product form ID (database:ID)
